Iraq faced escalating violence as insurgents intensified attacks on Iraqi and US targets, with at least 30 people killed.
Despite threats, Iraqi exiles in Australia and New Zealand voted early in historic national elections.
President Bush urged Iraqis to seize the "historic opportunity" to vote.
Insurgents murdered a candidate from Prime Minister Allawi's party, escalating tensions.
Attacks on polling stations resulted in casualties, including six killed in election-related violence.
The US military reported 400 Iraqis killed in January, highlighting the challenges leading up to the landmark elections.
Despite security measures, insurgents continued their deadly campaign.
